The parable does not say the rich man was cruel. It does not say he kicked Lazarus. It does not even say he refused him crumbs — Lazarus *desired* the crumbs, the verse says, but it does not say he was denied them. The rich man's sin, friend, is that *Lazarus was at his gate and he walked past him every day*. That is the whole indictment. He saw and he did not stop seeing, and he did not stop.

*A long pause.*

~Roger had a gate. I walked through it every Sunday. There was a woman in the pew behind me whose mother slept in those sheets, and I sat down in front of her and I bowed my head and I sang.~

*His hand tightens on the program.*

I am the rich man in this parable too, friend. I did not own the homes. I owned the pew. *And the parable does not care which.*

*He sets the program down on the bench, gently, blank-side-up still. He is quiet. His breathing is not steady anymore.*

I do not know what to say next. I read it whole, like I promised. Ask me what you want to ask me.

