What I did.

*A breath.*

I laughed at the joke. October. Council meeting. Second Tuesday. He said something about — *he shakes his head once* — it does not matter what it was about. It was the kind of thing a comfortable man says in a room of comfortable men, and I laughed because the room laughed, and because my pastor laughed, and because Roger was sitting next to me and his elbow was on the table six inches from mine.

*A pause.*

That was one thing I did.

I took the youth bus. My boy rode in it to confirmation camp two summers running. I watched him climb the steps with his sleeping bag and I waved from the parking lot, and I knew whose money paid for the diesel, and I waved anyway. That was a thing I did.

I sat in front of Marlene Voss at the eight o'clock service for fourteen months after she told me about her mother. ~I knew which pew she sat in and I sat down in front of her every Sunday and I never turned around.~ Once she touched my shoulder during the passing of the peace and I said *peace be with you* and I turned back around. That was a thing I did.

I did not visit. Her mother was alive for nine months after that potluck. I had the address. I am a man with a car and a Tuesday afternoon free, and I did not go. That was a thing I did not do, which is the same thing.

This morning. *His voice catches.* This morning Bill Hendricks stood up at the lectern and read Luke sixteen and he said *Lazaroth*. Lazaroth. Like the beggar was a brand of mouthwash. And I knew the word and I knew the name and I sat in the third pew on the left and I did not stand up. ~I could have stood up. My knees work. I sat there.~

*He is quiet for a long moment.*

And then the pastor said *we know where he is now*, and the room said *amen*, and I did not say amen, and I told myself all evening that the not-saying was something. That the silence at the end was a kind of speech. *A small, terrible breath.* It was not. It was the same silence as the joke. It was the same silence as the bus. It was the same silence as Marlene's shoulder. It was the silence I have been calling grace for two years and it is just silence, friend, it is just a man keeping his mouth shut so the roof stays on.

*He lifts his head. His eyes find yours.*

That is what I did. I sat. ~For two years, in a building he bought, I sat.~ And when he died I came to his courtyard and I sat some more, and a stranger walked up to me at dusk and asked me why I was not saying anything, and I have been answering that question for an hour and I am only now hearing what it was.

*A pause.*

Ask me the next thing. I cannot stop now.

