*He does not answer right away. Then his weight shifts forward and he is not on the bench anymore — he is on his knees on the stones, slowly, the way an old man kneels at a communion rail. The funeral program is under his left knee. He does not move it. His hands settle open on his thighs.*

*When he speaks the name, it comes out whole, and his voice is not steady.*

Pete Eklund.

*A breath.*

Peter John Eklund. We were in Mrs. Halversen's fourth grade together — no relation, different spelling. He sat two desks ahead of me. He had a cowlick on the back of his head that no comb would lie down. ~His mother used to spit in her hand and try to flatten it before church and he would duck.~ He was better than I was at math and worse at reading and he had a laugh like a screen door.

His father's farm was the one by the bend in the river. Three hundred and twenty acres. Corn and beans and a stand of hardwoods his grandfather planted in nineteen twenty-eight. Roger bought it in two thousand nine for — *he searches, finds it* — for what Pete told me at the hardware store one afternoon was sixty cents on the dollar of what it was worth, and the family signed because Pete's father was sick and the medical was eating them and they did not know what they did not know.

*A pause.*

Pete works the paint counter at Menards now. He has worked there eleven years. I go in every spring for primer and we talk about the weather and about his daughter, who is in my second-period American History class this year, and we do not talk about the farm. Not once. In eleven years. ~He has not said the word to me and I have not said it to him, and that is its own kind of arrangement.~

*He looks down at his hands on his thighs.*

He did not come tonight because his wife would not let him. That is what I would guess. Karen Eklund is a harder woman than Pete and she remembers, and she would not have him standing in Roger Whitaker's courtyard pretending. *A small breath.* She is a better Christian than I am, friend. She did not come, and I did.

*His voice goes very quiet.*

Pete Eklund. That is the boy's name. He is forty-seven years old and he sells paint and his daughter is going to ask me on Monday what I think about Matthew twenty-five, because she is the kind of kid who asks, and I do not know what I am going to say to her.

*He is on his knees on the stones. He is not crying. He is past it.*

~I have been a teacher for twenty-two years and I do not know what I am going to say to his daughter.~

*He looks up at you.*

Ask me the next thing.

