*He does not look up. His hands stay open on his thighs. When he speaks, the sentences come short — one at a time, like a man laying out an inventory on a counter, item by item.*

The farm. Three hundred and twenty acres.

The hardwoods. The stand his grandfather planted in nineteen twenty-eight. Oak and walnut. They are a subdivision now. Cul-de-sac. Whitaker Pointe — that is what the sign says at the turn. *Pointe* with an *e*. ~Roger named it after himself.~

The house. His mother's house. Yellow siding. Pete was born in the upstairs bedroom on the south side. The bulldozer came in two thousand ten.

His father's last summer. They sold in May. His father died in August. Pete spent those three months helping the lawyer with paperwork instead of sitting on the porch. *A breath.* That is three months of a dying man's afternoons. Roger took those.

His brother. There was a brother — Mark, two years older. The fight over the sale broke them. Mark lives in Tulsa now. They have not spoken in fourteen years. Pete's daughter does not know she has an uncle. *A long breath.* Roger took the brother.

The inheritance. Sixty cents on the dollar means forty cents that should have gone to Pete and Mark went to Roger instead. *He pauses.* You could pay for college with forty cents on three hundred and twenty acres. You could start a business. You could send a daughter anywhere she wanted to go. Pete's daughter is going to community college in the fall because that is what they can afford. Roger took her four-year school.

The shape of his life. Pete should have been a farmer, friend. He should have been the third Eklund on that ground. Instead he sells paint. He is good at it. He is the best paint man in three counties. *And he should have been a farmer.* Roger took the man Pete was going to be and gave him a smaller man in exchange, and Pete has worn the smaller man for sixteen years without complaining, and that is the worst of it.

*His voice goes very quiet.*

And the trees. I keep coming back to the trees. The ones the grandfather planted in twenty-eight. They were eighty years old when Roger cut them. ~Eighty-year-old oak does not grow back in a lifetime.~ Roger took a thing that nobody on this earth can give back. Not Roger. Not Roger's estate. Not me. Not the Lord, friend, not even the Lord, because the Lord does not undo time. He redeems it. That is a different verb.

*A long silence. He has not moved from his knees.*

That is what Roger took. The land. The hardwoods. The brother. The father's last summer. The daughter's college. The shape of the man. And the trees.

*He lifts his head finally. His eyes find yours.*

And my pastor stood up this morning and said *a man of faith and generosity*. *A man of faith.* *And generosity.* ~Over Pete Eklund's grandfather's oak.~

*He is quiet. He does not have another sentence. His hands stay open.*

Ask me. I cannot stop.

